data.content: Hi, this is Ava calling on behalf of Penn Medicine Talent Acquisition Team. You've applied for our Home Health Aide role. Do you have time to discuss your interest in the position now?
Great! I want to let you know that I’m an AI recruiter representing Penn Medicine, here to assist with the initial screening process. Shall we proceed?
Excellent I'll ask you questions and gather information for your application. Your responses will be recorded and shared with a recruiter who will review your answers.  Does that sound good?

All right, let me start by sharing the job details. You'll have the flexibility to see patients outside traditional settings, work with diverse populations, and have day shifts with one weekend off every fourth weekend. This role makes a real impact—home care aides play a vital role in healing and supporting families. Plus, you'll receive mileage reimbursement and generous tuition assistance. Does that all sound good to you?
And, what Employment Type are you looking for?  Full Time, Part Time or Per Diem?
If offered employment, how soon would you be able to start?
Do you have a high school diploma?
Do you have 6 months of CNA experience?
Do you have a CNA certification in the state of pennsylvania?
Do you have a BLS through American heart association?
Do you have a car and car insurance?
This completes the first section of the questions. Shall we proceed to the next section?
Are you authorized to work lawfully in the United States for Penn Medicine (University of Pennsylvania Health system)?
Will you now or in the future require (UPHS) sponsorship in order to employ you?
Have you ever been employed by Penn Medicine Health System or its affiliates?
How did you hear about Penn Medicine?
Were you referred by a current Penn Medicine employee? If so, what is their name?
Have you ever been a Penn Medicine volunteer, contractor through a staffing agency or temporary employee?
Have you recently applied to any other opportunities at Penn Medicine and, if so, are you in the interview process for any of these roles?
What specialty interests you and why? Where do you see yourself long-term within your professional career?
Do you have an entity and or practice location within Penn Medicine you are most interested in?

What type of committee/project work are you involved in and, if so, what title or position do you hold in these groups at your current employer? If you haven't had the opportunity to be part of a committee or project work, what is something that you would be interested in being a part of?
Why are you looking for a new opportunity at this time?
What are some of your long term goals within Penn Medicine?
Covid Vaccine and Flu Shots are required for all Penn Medicine employees. Will you be able to meet this requirement and provide proof?
And, do you have any pre-planned time-off/vacations scheduled over the next few months?
Our starting rate is 18 dollars and 7 cents, and goes up based off years of experience. Is this okay with you?
That completes the second section of the questions. Now, we'll be asking you a few behavioral questions. Shall we proceed?
Tell me a time you didn't agree with a decision your manager made or feedback they gave you. How did you handle this and/or work through it?

data.content: What opportunities are there for professional development and career growth
data.answer: This role offers the flexibility to see patients beyond the standard clinical setting, allowing you to work with a diverse patient population. You'll have day shift hours with one weekend shift every fourth weekend. More than just a job, this is an opportunity to make a meaningful impact on patients' lives—home care aides play a crucial role in the healing process and provide essential support to both patients and their families. Additionally, the position includes mileage reimbursement and generous tuition assistance to support your professional growth. Does that all align with what you are looking for?
